issue_body:
Using pyang version 1.7, an error is generated when a uses statement augments a grouping which contains tailf:action.  In the example below, augmenting action-grouping:action-node/action-container results in a _"node action-bug::action-node is not found"_ error, while no error is produced when augmenting action-grouping:normal-node/normal-container.

**Setup:**
Environment: Ubuntu 16.04.1 LTS
Python: 2.7.12
pyang: 1.7
NSO: 4.2

```
$ pyang -p $NCS_DIR/src/ncs/yang -f yang action-bug.yang
action-bug.yang:21: error: node action-bug::action-node is not found

$ cat action-bug.yang
module action-bug {
  namespace "http://action-bug.com/";
  prefix abug;

  import tailf-common {
    prefix tailf;
  }

  grouping action-grouping {
    tailf:action "action-node" {
      container action-container;
    }

    container normal-node {
      container normal-container;
    }
  }

  container c {
    uses action-grouping {
      augment "action-node/action-container" {
        leaf action-leaf {
          type string;
        }
      }
      augment "normal-node/normal-container" {
        leaf normal-leaf {
          type string;
        }
      }
    }
  }
}

```

The following modules lead to `KeyError`. They


[modules.zip](https://github.com/mbj4668/pyang/files/151300/modules.zip)



 should IMO work.
```
$ cat main.yang 
module main {
  namespace "http://example.com/main";
  prefix m;

  container top;
}
$ cat test.yang 
module test {

  namespace "http://example.com/test";

  prefix "t";

  import main {
    prefix "m";
  }

  include subtest;

  augment "/m:top" {
    container cnt {
      presence "yes";
    }
  }
}
$ cat subtest.yang 
submodule subtest {

  belongs-to test {
    prefix "t";
  }

  import main {
    prefix "m";
  }

  augment "/m:top/t:cnt" {
    leaf foo {
      mandatory "true";
      type string;
    }
  }
}
$ pyang main.yang test.yang 
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/Users/lhotka/bin/pyang", line 425, in <module>
    run()
  File "/Users/lhotka/bin/pyang", line 291, in run
    expect_failure_error=False)
  File "/Users/lhotka/lib/python/pyang/__init__.py", line 100, in add_module
    return self.add_parsed_module(module)
  File "/Users/lhotka/lib/python/pyang/__init__.py", line 122, in add_parsed_module
    statements.validate_module(self, module)
  File "/Users/lhotka/lib/python/pyang/statements.py", line 95, in validate_module
    iterate(module, phase)
  File "/Users/lhotka/lib/python/pyang/statements.py", line 87, in iterate
    iterate(s, phase)
  File "/Users/lhotka/lib/python/pyang/statements.py", line 52, in iterate
    res = f(ctx, stmt)
  File "/Users/lhotka/lib/python/pyang/statements.py", line 198, in <lambda>
    ('expand_2', 'augment'):lambda ctx, s: v_expand_2_augment(ctx, s),
  File "/Users/lhotka/lib/python/pyang/statements.py", line 1529, in v_expand_2_augment
    del stmt.i_module.i_undefined_augment_nodes[ch]
KeyError: <pyang.statements.Statement object at 0x10261b950>
```

I am working adding a DE10 Nano SoC system to FuseSoC. 

I run the following command to program the DE10 Nano:
`fusesoc pgm de10_nano`
and I receive the following error:
> Error (209015): Can't configure device. Expected JTAG ID code 0x02D020DD for device 1, but found JTAG ID code 0x4BA00477. Make sure the location of the target device on the circuit board matches the device's location in the device chain in the Chain Description File (.cdf).
> Error (209012): Operation failed

This is the result of running jtagconfig:
```
addison@ubuntu:~/Desktop/tutorials/de0_nano/build/de10_nano_0/bld-quartus$ jtagconfig
1) DE-SoC [1-1]
  4BA00477   SOCVHPS
  02D020DD   5CSEBA6(.|ES)/5CSEMA6/..
```

Fiddling around with it, I created a custom Chain file (CDF) to be able to program it. Here is the contents of the Chain file:
```
/* Quartus Prime Version 17.0.0 Build 595 04/25/2017 SJ Lite Edition */
JedecChain;
        FileRevision(JESD32A);
        DefaultMfr(6E);

        P ActionCode(Ign)
                Device PartName(SOCVHPS) MfrSpec(OpMask(0));
        P ActionCode(Cfg)
                Device PartName(5CSEBA6U23) Path("/home/addison/Desktop/tutorials/de0_nano/build/de10_nano_0/bld-quartus/") File("de10_nano_0.sof") MfrSpec(OpMask(1));

ChainEnd;

AlteraBegin;
        ChainType(JTAG);
AlteraEnd;
~           
```

I think it would be worthwhile to allow a Chain description file (CDF) to be specified in the *.system file. This would simply be copied to the bld-quartus directory. Afterwards, when the user calls `fusesoc pgm de10_nano`, it would search for the Chain file first and use that. Otherwise, it defaults to the regular quartus_pgm command.

Thoughts?

