I have a model, Rx with a FK relationship to another model, Entry.  In admin Rx is setup as an inline for Entry.  When a new Rx instance is added, that instance is added to every revision in that Entry's history, not just the most recent.  I am using admin to register the models, and middleware to create revisions.  Is this normal behavior?  

models.py

    class Entry(models.Model):
        ...
    
    class Rx(models.Model):
        entry = models.ForeignKey(Entry)
        ...
    
admin.py

    class RxInline(admin.TabularInline):
        model = Rx
    
    class EntryAdmin(reversion.VersionAdmin):
        inlines = [RxInline]

Partials updates (via PATCH request) is throwing a KeyError in [_pop_tags]( https://github.com/glemmaPaul/django-taggit-serializer/blob/master/taggit_serializer/serializers.py#L48
) when the 'tags' field's data is not included in the patch request.  

In our situation, we patch a lot of records, and we only patch the fields that change.

__Current implementation__
```python
    def _pop_tags(self, validated_data):
        to_be_tagged = {}

        for key in self.fields.keys():
            field = self.fields[key]
            if isinstance(field, TagListSerializerField):
                to_be_tagged[key] = validated_data.pop(key)

        return (to_be_tagged, validated_data)
```

We need the check the existence of the key before pop'ing it, correct?

```python
    def _pop_tags(self, validated_data):
        to_be_tagged = {}

        for key in self.fields.keys():
            field = self.fields[key]
            if isinstance(field, TagListSerializerField):
                if key in validated_data:
                    to_be_tagged[key] = validated_data.pop(key)

        return (to_be_tagged, validated_data)
```

I'm happy to open a PR, but wanted to make sure I wasn't missing something simple or overthinking it.

Trainer.eta can be modified directly as in
https://github.com/clab/dynet/blob/master/examples/cpp/rnnlm/train_rnnlm.cc#L271-L272
```
if (eta_decay_onset_epoch && completed_epoch >= (int)eta_decay_onset_epoch)
  sgd->eta *= eta_decay_rate;
```

Trainer.update_epoch() increments epoch and changes eta according to eta0, epoch and eta_decay, regardless of current eta.
https://github.com/clab/dynet/blob/master/dynet/training.h#L72
```
void update_epoch(real r = 1) {
  epoch += r;
  eta = eta0 / (1 + epoch * eta_decay);
  }
```

So it looks that if eta is changed directly and update_epoch is called after that, the first change to eta is cancelled.
Maybe it's intended but it looks confusing to me.

